          const networkCalls: Observable&lt;any&gt;[] = [];
          var i;
          for (i = 1; i &lt; 11; i++) {
            networkCalls.push(this.apiService.addUsers(i));
          }
          forkJoin(networkCalls).subscribe(
            resultArray =&gt; {
              this.arrBirds = resultArray;
              console.log(this.arrBirds);
            },
            (err: HttpErrorResponse) =&gt; {
              console.log(err.message);
            }
          );

 All network requests are stored as `Observable` in the `networkCalls` array and then fired at once using `forkJoin` on the array. This returns the response of all calls in a single array which can be directly assigned to `this.arrBirds`.

 3. `addUsers` method is using `y` directly in the URL as a string. The value of `y` should be used instead. You also have the baseUrl for the API stored. So, you could construct the url using template literals. I have renamed `x` to `baseUrl` and `y` to `userId` for better understanding.

